<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-22T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-22T03:00:00-05:00" n="186" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5437: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-22T16:00:00+08:00">July 22, 1932—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 22—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>839. Following from American Consul at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“July 22, 11 a.m. According to a reliable source, official
                                    spokesman of Japanese military headquarters said unofficially
                                    that if <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CH2">Chang
                                        Hsueh-liang</persName> sends troops into Jehol it will be
                                    considered a hostile act.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>